North Korea says there is "no chance" of unilateral disarmament as long as there is no confidence
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that extending sanctions would deepen distrust of the United States and that it is impossible for his country to unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons in such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the annual General Assembly of the global council that North Korea had implemented “significant measures to prove its good faith” last year, such as the cessation of nuclear tests and missile tests, the dismantling of the nuclear test site, and the commitment to nuclear non-proliferation and weapons non-proliferation.
"However, we do not see any appropriate response from the United States," he said.
“If we can’t trust the United States, we won’t trust our national security capabilities and, in such circumstances, we can’t disarm unilaterally first.”
Although Ri reiterated North Korea's familiar objections to Washington's opposition to a "scalar" approach to denuclearization, according to which North Korea would be rewarded if it took gradual steps, his statement seemed significant because he did not directly reject the past unilateral denuclearization.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump as part of a first-ever summit between a U.S. president and the North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, where Kim pledged to make progress towards a “denuclearization of the Korean peninsula,” while Trump offered the North’s guarantees.
North Korea sought an official end to the 1950-1953 Korean War, but the United States said Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
In addition, Washington has not responded to demands to relax the harsh international sanctions imposed on North Korea.
“The United States insists on the option of ‘denuclearization first’ and increases pressure through sanctions to achieve its goal in a coercive way, even objecting to the ‘declaration of an end to war’,” Ri said.
“The impression that sanctions can kneel is an illusion that only people who don’t know us have.
But the problem is that prolonged sanctions deepen our mistrust.”
Ri did not mention plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump that the U.S. leader referred to at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted the three meetings between Kim and Moon Jae-in, the president of South Korea, over the past five months, adding: "If the issue of denuclearization had been negotiated with South Korea and not the United States, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not have reached this impasse."
Even in these conditions, Ri’s tone of speech was very different from last year’s, when he told the UN General Assembly that it was inevitable to target U.S. territory with missiles from North Korea after “Mr. Evil President” Trump called Kim a “missile man.”
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened North Korea with “total destruction,” praised Kim for his courage to initiate the disarmament process, but said work was just beginning and that sanctions would remain in place until North Korea was denuclearized.
On Wednesday, Trump said there was no planned period for this, adding: “It doesn’t matter if it lasts two or three years or five months.”
China and Russia say Pyongyang should be rewarded by the UN Security Council for the measures taken.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council on Thursday: “The implementation of the Security Council sanctions must continue vigorously and without interruption until we achieve complete, final and confirmed denuclearization.”
The Security Council unanimously increased sanctions imposed on North Korea since 2006, in an attempt to block funds for Pyongyang’s nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met with Ri on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly and later said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times this year, but the last visit did not have very good results.
When he left Pyongyang in July, he said progress had been made, but after just a few hours, North Korea denounced him as having made “gangster threats.”
At a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea pledged to dismantle a missile launch ramp and a nuclear complex if the United States takes “appropriate action.”
He said Kim had told him that the "appropriate measures" he was looking for were the security guarantees Trump had promised in Singapore and that he wanted normalization of relations with Washington.
Harvard students take classes on how to get enough rest
A new course from Harvard University this year encourages students to sleep longer in an attempt to combat the growing “macho” culture that makes them undergo “all night” learning sessions energized with high levels of caffeine.
A scientist has discovered that, often, students at the world’s most prestigious university don’t even master the basic concepts of how they should take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, is the one who created the course, believed to be the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to create the course after holding a conference on the impact of lack of sleep on the ability to learn.
“In the end, a girl came to me and said, ‘Why is this only being told to me now, in the last year?’
She told me that she had never been talked about the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, first introduced this year, explains to students the essential concepts of how good sleep habits help improve academic and athletic performance, as well as general well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after finding that students were seriously sleep deprived during the week.
The one-hour course can involve a number of interactive tasks.
In one section, the image of a living room is presented, and students can click on coffee mugs, curtains, sports pants and books to tell them what the effects of caffeine and light are and how athletic performance is affected by sleep deficiency, but also about the importance of a sleep program.
In another section, participants were told how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression, and cancer.
A map of the campus, with interactive icons, encourages participants to think about their daily schedule.
“We know we can’t instantly change the behavior of students.
But we believe that they have the right to know, just as everyone has the right to know what the health effects of smoking are,” added Professor Czeisler.
The culture that makes students proud that they learned all night still exists, he says, adding that modern technology and the increasing pressure placed on students have turned sleep deprivation into a growing problem.
Sufficient sleep, of good quality, should be a student’s “secret weapon” to combat stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said, and even to avoid weight gain, because sleep deprivation makes the brain believe that the body is hungry, which makes students constantly feel that they are hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old California student studying chemistry and physics, helped Professor Czeisler create the course after attending one of his classes in his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to promote a course for all students.
The next step, he hopes, is to require all postgraduate students to complete a similar degree program before enrolling in this institution where competition is fierce.
Professor Czeisler advised students to schedule an alarm to know when it is time to go to bed, as well as for waking hours, and to know what are the damaging effects of the “blue light” emitted by electronic screens and LEDs, which can disrupt the circadian rhythm and cause difficulty in arming.
