He wanted to prove that he was “someone,” he said, so he didn’t disappoint everyone when they finally found out about his sexuality.
The Olympic bronze medalist has become a prominent supporter of LGBT campaigns and took advantage of appearing at this year’s Commonwealth Games in Australia to urge more countries to decriminalize homosexuality.
He said he decided to speak because he felt lucky that he could live freely, without a trace, and because he wanted to give others “hope.”
