The National Trust is spying on the secret lives of bats.
New research that is being conducted on a property in the Scottish Highlands wants to reveal how bats use the environment to hunt their prey.
It is hoped that the findings will reveal new things about the behavior of these unprecedented flying mammals and help future conservation activities.
The study, conducted by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland, will analyze common dwarf bats and pigmeat bats, as well as ear bats and water bats from Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recording equipment will be placed in key locations around the property to monitor the activity of bats during the season.
The NHS team and volunteers will also conduct mobile studies using manual detectors.
A specialized audio analysis of all recordings will estimate the frequency of sounds made by bats and what species emit certain sounds.
A map of the habitat and a report will be produced to create a detailed, scaled image of their behavior in the environment.
Rob Dewar, a nature conservation consultant for NTS, hopes the results will reveal which habitat areas are most important for bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as creating lawn, and what is the best way to maintain forest meadows for bats and other associated species.
Flea populations in Scotland and across the UK have declined considerably in the last century.
They are endangered by the construction and development work that affects their nests, but also by the loss of habitat.
And wind turbines and public lighting are risks, as are fly traps and some chemical treatments for building materials, but also attacks from domestic cats.
In fact, bats are not blind.
However, because they hunt at night, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated ecolocation technique to accurately identify insects and obstacles on their flight path.
NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 major parks and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, is thinking very seriously about bats.
They have ten trained experts, who regularly conduct studies, control the nests and sometimes carry out rescue missions.
The organization created the first and only bat reserve in Scotland, on the Threave estate in Dumfries and Galloway, where eight out of ten bat species are found in Scotland.
The farm manager, David Thompson, says this is the ideal territory for bats.
“Here at Threave, the area is great for bats,” he says.
“We have old buildings, a lot of old trees and a perfect habitat.
But there’s a lot we don’t know about bats, so the work we do here and elsewhere will help us understand why they need to multiply.”
It emphasizes the importance of looking for bats before performing maintenance work on properties, as the simple unintentional destruction of a maternal nest could kill up to 400 females and chicks, which can destroy the entire local population.
Fleas are protected, and killing, harassing or disturbing them, as well as destroying their nests, are prohibited actions.
Elisabeth Ferrell, a Scottish official at the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to help them.
She said: “We still have a lot to learn about bats and we don’t know how populations evolve for many of our species.”
