Earthquakes and tsunamis in Indonesia
At least 384 people have been killed in a strong earthquake and tsunami that hit the Indonesian city of Palu on Friday, authorities said, and the death toll is expected to increase.
Due to the disruption of communications networks, authorities dealing with disasters were unable to obtain any information from the Donggala Regency, an area in the northern city of Palu, which is closer to the epicenter of the 7.5-degree earthquake on the Richter scale.
In Palu, more than 16,000 people were evacuated after the disaster.
Here are some key information about Palu and Donggala, from the island of Sulawesi:
Palu is the capital of the province of central Sulawesi, located at the end of a narrow bay on the west coast of Sulawesi, with a population of about 379,800 in 2017.
The city was celebrating 40 years of existence when it was hit by a tsunami and an earthquake.
Donggala is a regency that stretches along a coast with an area of more than 300 km in the northwest of the island of Sulawesi.
The Regency, an administrative region located at the bottom of a province, has a population of about 299.200 in 2017.
Fishing and agriculture activities are the central point of the economy of the central Sulawesi province, especially the Donggala coastal region.
Mining activities for nickel extraction are also important in the province, but are concentrated mainly in Morowali, on the opposite coast of Sulawesi Island.
Palu and Donggala have been hit by tsunamis several times in the last 100 years, according to the Indonesian Disaster Management Agency.
In 1938, a tsunami killed more than 200 people and destroyed hundreds of homes in Donggala.
Also in 1996, a tsunami struck the western part of the Donggala Regency, killing nine people.
Indonesia is in the Pacific Fire Circle, an area of intense seismic activity.
Here are some of the earthquakes and tsunamis that have occurred in recent years:
2004: On December 26, a strong earthquake on the west coast of Indonesia's Aceh province, in the north of Sumatra Island, triggered a tsunami that struck 14 countries, killing 226,000 people on the coast of the Indian Ocean, more than half of them from Aceh.
2005: A series of strong earthquakes hit the west coast of the island of Sumatra in late March and early April.
Hundreds of people have died on the island of Nias, off the coast of Sumatra.
2006: A magnitude 6.8 earthquake on the Richter scale hit the south of Indonesia's most populous island, Java, triggering a tsunami that hit the south coast, killing nearly 700 people.
2009: A magnitude 7.6 earthquake on the Richter scale occurred near Padang, the capital of West Sumatra province.
More than 1,100 people were killed.
2010: A 7.5-degree earthquake on the Richter scale hit one of the Mentawai islands off the coast of Sumatra Island, triggering a 10-metre-high tsunami that destroyed dozens of villages and killed around 300 people.
2016: A low-intensity earthquake occurred in the Pidie Jaya regency in Aceh, causing damage and panic as people remembered the devastating 2004 earthquake and tsunami, which resulted in a large number of deaths.
There was no tsunami this time, but more than 100 people died as a result of the collapse of buildings.
2018: Several powerful earthquakes have occurred on the tourist island of Lombok, causing the deaths of more than 500 people, most on the northern side of the island.
