Syria is ready for the return of refugees, says Foreign Minister
Syria says it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and calls for help to rebuild the country devastated by a war that has lasted for more than seven years.
During his speech at the United Nations General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem said the situation in the country is improving.
"Today, conditions on the ground are more stable and secure, thanks to the progress made in combating terrorism," he said.
The government continues to rehabilitate areas destroyed by terrorists so that things return to normal.
The existing conditions allow refugees to voluntarily return to the country they were forced to leave because of terrorism and unilateral economic measures aimed at their daily lives.
The United Nations estimates that more than 5.5 million Syrians have fled the country since 2011 when the war broke out.
Six million people still living in the country are in need of humanitarian assistance.
Al-Moualem said the Syrian regime would be happy to receive help to rebuild the devastated country.
But he stressed that conditional assistance or assistance from countries sponsored by the insurgency will not be accepted.
