Red tide news: concentrations have fallen in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Wildlife Protection Commission shows a general drop in red tide concentrations for certain areas of the Gulf of Tampa.
According to the Commission, uneven inflorescence conditions are reported in the Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties – suggesting decreasing concentrations.
This red tide inflorescence extends over a coastal area of about 210 km, from the north of Pinellas County to the south of Lee County.
The spots can be found about 16 km across Hillsborough County, but in fewer places than last week.
The red tide was also observed in Pasco County.
The average concentrations found in or near Pinellas county were reported last week as well as low to high concentrations in Hillsborough county, low to high concentrations in Manatee county, low to high concentrations in Sarasota county, and high concentrations in or near Sarasota county.
Respiratory tract irritation continues to be reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
No cases of respiratory tract irritation have been reported in the northwestern state of Florida in the past week.
